tford (Northumberland), Hartforth in Gilling (North Yorkshire), Hartford (Cheshire), or Hertford (Hertfordshire); less probably from Hartford End in Felsted (Essex) or Hartfordbridge in Elvetham (Hampshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>heorot</i> ‘hart, stag’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":27,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Hertford of London was born in 1263, in London, Middlesex, England. He married Mrs Robert Hertford before 1289, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1314, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1263–1314":"1263–1314","–Female":"Surnud","1289–Female":"1289–Surnud","1314":"1314","before 1289":"enne 1289","1289":"1289","1263":"1263","1290":"1290","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, Englan